 book marks the first time that historians and archaeologists of Egypt, the Near East, Greece, and Rome have come together with sociologists, political scientists, and economists, to ask whether the differences between accounts of these regions reflect real economic differences in the past, or are merely a function of variations in the surviving evidence and the intellectual traditions that have grown up around it. The contributors describe the types of evidence available and demonstrate the need for clearer thought about the relationships between evidence and models in ancient economic history, laying the foundations for a new comparative account of economic structures and growth in the ancient Mediterranean world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aAmemiya, Takeshi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBagnall, Roger S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBedford, Peter R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, John K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGranovetter, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreif, Avner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHitchner, R. Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiverani, Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManning, J. G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManning, J.G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMorris, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorris, Ian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSaller, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://i